{{essay-like|date=January 2018}}
'''Radio art''', refers to the use of [[radio]] for [[art]].

The artist who works in radio art is not necessarily a trained DJ, programmer, producer, or engineer, but one who uses sound to make art. The radio [[Art medium|medium]] can be used in ways which are different from what it  was intended for.<ref name=autogenerated2>[http://okno.be/?id=964 A contemporary look on radio art] by okno staff.</ref> In that sense, the way the message is transmitted and received by an audience is as important as the message itself. "As an aural art form it reaffirms that it's not just what we say, but the way we say it." <ref name=autogenerated1>[http://transition.turbulence.org/somewhere/NAR/writings/apple.htm New American Radio and Radio Art]{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} by [[Jacki Apple]].</ref> In Victoria Fenner's words, "Radio art is art which is specifically composed for the [[Art medium|medium]] of radio and is uniquely suited to be transmitted via the [[radio wave|airwaves]]." <ref>[http://www.magneticspirits.com/history.html Radio Art and its History] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081121221712/http://www.magneticspirits.com/history.html |date=2008-11-21 }} by Victoria Fenner, Canadian sound artist and radio producer.</ref>

Artists use [[:Category:Radio technology|radio technology]] (i.e. radio [[Transmission (telecommunications)|transmission]], [[radio wave|airwaves]]...) to communicate artistic compositions for interpretation – exposing their audience to alternate means to experiencing their art through [[sound]] verses visualization. Radio Art contributes to new media art - a digitally driven art movement growing in response to the informative technological revolution we live in. “From the artist's point of view radio is an environment to be entered into and acted upon, a site for various cultural voices to meet, converse, and merge in. These artists cross disciplines, raid all genres and recontextualize them into hybrids.” <ref name=autogenerated1 />

Radio art projects can be collaborative including various professional sources, unifying an [[Sound recording and reproduction|audio]] broadcast with science, experimentation, geography, entertainment, etc." Some have approached radio as an architectural space to be constructed sonically and linguistically; or as the site of an event, an arena, or stage. Some used it as a gathering place, or a conduit, a means to create community. Other artists have employed the [[Mass media|media]] landscape itself as the narrative, while others looked into the body as the site and the source; the voicebox, the larynx become medium and metaphor." <ref name=autogenerated1 />

== Styles ==

[[radio documentary]], [[radio drama]], [[soundscape]], [[sound art]], [[electroacoustic music]], [[sound poetry]], [[performance]], [[open source]], [[translation]], [[interviews]], audio galleries, [[soundscape]], [[sound art]], [[electroacoustic music]], [[sound poetry]] intended for the radio, [[spoken word]], [[concerts]], experimental [[narratives]], sonic geographies, pseudo documentaries, radio cinema, conceptual and [[multimedia]] performances intended for the radio.

== Art radio and webradio ==

An art radio is a radio station that would dedicate every second of its transmission time to radio art. Although this kind of project can seem utopian in the traditional state of [[radio]], there are few lasting experiences in the underground or community side such as London's [[ResonanceFM]] which intend to make radio with art and promote the ''art of listening''.

Also, radio had renewed itself through the [[Internet]]. The audio streaming technique had replaced the analogue transmitting system and artists can experiment on radio outside the legal constraints of an FM license for example. 
Among the webradios which are dedicated to radio art, some broadcast pieces like traditional [[radios]]. Some others directly experiment with the [[Art medium|medium]] in the more concrete sense. Radio Astronomy<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radio-astronomy.net|title=radio astronomy: a project by r a d i o q u a l i a|website=www.radio-astronomy.net}}</ref> [[broadcast]] [[sounds]] taken from outer space in real time. Le Poulpe<ref>{{cite web|url=http://poulpe.apo33.org|title=start [POULPE]|website=poulpe.apo33.org}}</ref> is a networking experimental radio that mix several "spaces" processed and streamed through the Internet.

