'''Zahra Kamalkhani''' (born 1954) is an Iranian anthropologist.<ref name="Sleeman2001">{{cite book|author=Elizabeth Sleeman|title=The International Who's Who of Women 2002|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6J8xDWDqOkEC&pg=PA284|year=2001|publisher=Psychology Press|isbn=978-1-85743-122-3|page=284}}</ref>
Zahra Kamalkhani was educated at the [[University of Tehran]], [[University of Bergen]] and [[SOAS]].<ref name="Sleeman2001"/> She started teaching the anthropology of [[gender]] and [[Middle Eastern studies]] at the University of Bergen in 1986, completing her PhD there in 1996. She subsequently conducted post-doctoral research at [[Edith Cowan University]] and the [[University of Western Australia]].<ref name="AkbarzadehSaeed2001">{{cite book|author1=Shahram Akbarzadeh|author2=Abdullah Saeed|title=Muslim Communities in Australia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ERsRbpV8P5oC&pg=PR9|year=2001|publisher=UNSW Press|isbn=978-0-86840-580-3|page=ix}}</ref>
==Works== * ''Iranian immigrants and refugees in Norway'', 1983 * ''Women's Everyday Religious Discourse in Iran'', 1993<ref>Kamalkhani, Zahra. 1993. "Women's Everyday Religious Discourse in Iran." In Women in the Middle East: Perceptions, Realities, and Struggles for Liberation, by Haleh Afshar, 85-95. New York: St. Martin's Press.</ref> * ''Women's Islam: religious practice among women in today's Iran'', 1996
